    <stitle>Electrical System Troubleshooting Guide - BE 200, CE 200, CE 300 Model - BODY FEATURES - ELECTRIC HORNS
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec id="x08290116">
        <title>ELECTRIC HORNS</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="1">
            <title>Circuit Functions</title>
            <para>Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="f08290906">electric horn function diagram</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f08290906" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg08/G08290906.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Electric Horn Function Diagram</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. ELECTRIC HORNS, RIGHT SIDE #2 (8312) &#38; LEFT SIDE #1 (8311)</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. ELECTRICAL SYSTEM CONTROLLER</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. CIRCUITS TO ESC CONNECTOR (1600)</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. ELECTRIC HORN SWITCH IN STEERING WHEEL</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <para>The electric horns provide the driver audio warning to warn others.</para>
            <para>The electric horn switch is a direct input (not multiplexed) to the ESC. When the horn button is
                pushed the ESC provides voltage to the horns. The circuits from the steering wheel travel through a
                clock spring assembly which is used instead of a slip ring assembly. Its winds and unwinds as the wheel
                is turned.
            </para>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
